\begin_layout Standard
A sequence of states at times 
\begin_inset Formula $t=n\Delta t$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a positive integer, forming a discrete sampling of a path can be obtained
 from the following iteration
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{x}_{n+1}=\boldsymbol{\Lambda}\boldsymbol{x}_{n}+\sqrt{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}\,\boldsymbol{\xi}_{n},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}$
\end_inset

 is a matrix square-root (usually the Cholesky factor) of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\xi}_{n}\sim\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{0},\boldsymbol{I})$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-dimensional uncorrelated normal variate with zero mean and unit variance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now consider the case of a Brownian harmonic oscillator where the position
 and the velocity are determined from the above recursion relation.
 The form of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

 matrices can then be obtained following the expressions in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "norrelykke2011harmonic"

\end_inset

.
 Their explicit forms are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\Lambda}=\exp\left(-\Delta t/2\tau\right)\left[\cos(\omega\Delta t)\mathbf{I}+\sin(\omega\Delta t)\mathbf{J}\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{J}$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{I}=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix},\qquad\bm{J}=\frac{1}{\omega}\begin{pmatrix}1/2\tau & 1\\
-\omega_{0}^{2} & -1/2\tau
\end{pmatrix},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 are the particle mass and friction coefficient.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=\sqrt{k/m}$
\end_inset

 is the cyclic frequency of the underdamped oscillation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=m/\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the characteristic time scale and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\sqrt{k/m-\gamma^{2}/(4m^{2})}$
\end_inset

 is the frequency of the damped oscillator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The form of the matrix square-root 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{L}=\sqrt{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{L}=\begin{pmatrix}L_{1} & 0\\
L_{3}/L_{1} & \sqrt{L_{2}^{2}-L_{3}^{3}/L_{1}^{2}}
\end{pmatrix},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


